Base.Explanation: Get information from a file or directory. The information includes the existence of the file or directory, type information (file or directory), attributes, creation, access times and size.

ArrayElement.Name: Target file/directory
ArrayElement.Description: The name of target file or directory. Can be specified using the full UNC path (recommended) or local path (local to the UMRA Service or Console application). Example: \\SERVER_A\Share_b\Directory_1\File.ext, \\SERVER_A\Share_b\Directory_1\Dir2, G:\UserData\John.

ArrayElement.Name: File/dir exists flag
ArrayElement.Description: Output only property. When specified, the output variable value is set to 'Yes' if the file or directory exists.

ArrayElement.Name: Is directory flag
ArrayElement.Description: Output only property. When specified, the output variable value is set to 'Yes' if the target path identifies a directory.

ArrayElement.Name: Attributes
ArrayElement.Description: Output only property. When specified, the output variable value is set equal to the attribute mask of the file or directory.

ArrayElement.Name: Creation time
ArrayElement.Description: Output only property. When specified, the output variable value is set to the creation time of the file or directory.

ArrayElement.Name: Last access time
ArrayElement.Description: Output only property. When specified, the output variable value is set to the last access time of the file or directory.

ArrayElement.Name: Last write time
ArrayElement.Description: Output only property. When specified, the output variable value is set to the last write time of the file or directory.

ArrayElement.Name: Size
ArrayElement.Description: Output only property. When specified, the output variable value is set to size of the file in bytes (meaningless value for directories: 0).

ArrayElement.Name: Error if not found
ArrayElement.Description: Set to 'Yes' if this action should produce an error in case the file or directory does not exist. Default value: 'No'.

Base.Explanation: Execute a command line. The command line can contain any valid command (.exe, .bat, .com, etc.) with any number of command line arguments. Further, the command line can contain variables.

ArrayElement.Name: Command Line
ArrayElement.Description: The command line that must be executed. The command line starts with the name of a file that can be executed (.exe, .bat, etc.) and a number of arguments.

ArrayElement.Name: Wait until terminated
ArrayElement.Description: Once the command is started, the application can either wait until the command has been terminated or continue immediately with the rest of the script.

ArrayElement.Name: Time-out period
ArrayElement.Description: The period specifies the maximum number of seconds the command can take to complete. When the command is not completed within the time-out period, the command is terminated. If this property is specified, the property 'Wait until terminated' must also be specified. When this value is not specified, a default value of one hour is used.

ArrayElement.Name: Show command window
ArrayElement.Description: The application can either hide or show a window that is created by the command.

ArrayElement.Name: Output variable
ArrayElement.Description: Store the output of the command in the specified variable.

ArrayElement.Name: Remove carriage-return line-feed
ArrayElement.Description: If property 'Output variable' is specified, the value will often end with the characters carriage return - line feed. Specify 'Yes' to remove these characters from the end of hte command line output. Default value: 'No'.

ArrayElement.Name: Output buffer size
ArrayElement.Description: Optional: When specified, the application reserves a buffer of the specified size in bytes to store the output data in a variable. By default (not specified), the maximum size is 10240 bytes. If the real output data size exceeds the limit, the data is not stored. Example value: 250000.

ArrayElement.Name: Do not show in log file
ArrayElement.Description: Set to 'Yes' if the command line should not be shown in the log file. Default setting (not specified): 'No'.

Base.Explanation: Delete an existing object from Active Directory. The object can be a group, user, OU etc. The object is specified by either a variable, LDAP name or SAM account name.

ArrayElement.Name: Active Directory Object
ArrayElement.Description: A data structure representing the object. This property can only be specified by a variable of which the value is obtained in a previously executed script action, typically 'Get object (AD)'. The object to delete must be specified by one of the properties (1) Active Directory Object, (2) LDAP name or (3) SAM account name.

ArrayElement.Name: LDAP name
ArrayElement.Description: The LDAP name of the object to be deleted. Example: LDAP:://DC_1/CN=GroupA,OU=Students,DC=domain,DC=com. The object to delete must be specified by one of the properties (1) Active Directory Object, (2) LDAP name or (3) SAM account name.

ArrayElement.Name: SAM account name
ArrayElement.Description: The SAM account name of the object to be deleted. Example: DOMAIN_45\GroupA. The object to delete must be specified by one of the properties (1) Active Directory Object, (2) LDAP name or (3) SAM account name.
